{"/service/ndnp/ct/batch_ct_inxs_ver01/data/sn82014519/00414183566/1930100701/0650.xml":{"full_text":"NEW BRITAIN DAILY HERALD, TUESDAY, OCTOBER 7, 1930.\n5-'\nONLY 9 CONFINED\nON DEVIL'S ISLE\nThree Aviators Among Lifers at\nFrench Penal Colony\nDouthit's Homer Starts Card Barrage\nWEDNESDAY always BARGAIN DAY\nWashington, D. C Oct. 7 How\nDevil's Island, famous penal station\nin French Guiana, looks from the\nair is told in a report to the Nj\ntional Geographic Society by Fred\nerick Simpich,. recently in charge of\nthe society's aerial .survey party\nwhich made a study of air traffic\nlanes between Washington and\nBuenos Aires.\n\"With M. .Siadous, Governor Gen\neral of French Guiana,\" writes Mr.\nHimpicK. \"we flew from Cayenne lo\ndevil's Island. Here Captain Drey\nfus lanjjuished through long, lonely\nyears till freed by Emile Zola's aid.\nHis dramatic trial, uncovering the\namazing Count Esterhazy plot,,\nstirred the civilized world.\n\"Three tiny green dots rise from\nthe sea 21! miles south of Cayenne.\nThey form the penal group, 'Isles\ndu Salut,' which include 'St. Joseph\n-r-.with, its prison hospital Isle\nRoyale, with tiers of tiny stone cells\nfor incorrigibles, and Devil's is\nland, so famed in tales of fact and\nfiction.\n\"Men without women gazed up\nfrom behind high walls as we idled\noverhead. For women are no longer\nKent to this 'great penitentiary of\nFrance.' Here, and in Cayenne are\nabout 7,000 French prisoners in\ncluding such colonials as Arabs, Af\nricans and even French Indo\nChinese. Island of Spies\n\"But on Devil's Island today, de\nspite its world-wide notoriety only\nnine men are confined mostly\nspies. But they are lifers. Three\naviators \"are there. They were\namong the little group gazing up at\nat us. I wondered what their\nthoughts must be, as they saw, our\nbig ship flying free in their own\nonce familiar element able to\ncarry them so quickly to freedom\nwere they only up in it. Hard\nby, on Isle Royale, are prison\ngraves row on row, where now men\nof high and low degree sleep sid,.-.\nby side, their earthly penalties paid.\n\"A dismal land is Cayenne, or\nFrench Guiana, as you fly from\nParamaribo along its lonely coast.\nMud flats far out to sea, brightened\nonly by flocks of two thousand or\nmore pink ibis, and low, jungle\ngrown swamps broken by grassy\nsavannas stretching inland to dis\ntant low hills. Once past the planta\ntions below Paramaribo, so many\nlong abandoned, the only signs of\nwhite man's work we saw were\nabout the mouth of the River Ma\nroni. Up it steamers go, some to un\nload prisoners for the penal colo\nnies. The last ship brought about\nS00 from France.\n\"Returning from Devil's Island,\nwe took Governor Siadous for a\nrid over the delta of the Kourou.\nIt was up this river that a French\ncolonizing company once sent 10,\n000 immigrants from Alsace. Badly\nequipped, unwisely chosen for the\nparty included jewelers, dancing\nmasters and even dressmakers but\nfew experienced farmers or miners\nnearly all perished. That disaster\nis historic. Only about 2,000 surviv\ned, and returned to France.\nRich Soil But No Farmers\n\"Miles inland we could see low.\ntree-painted ridges, with round-top\nhills enjoying such local names as\nMonkey Hill and Devil Mountain.\nInto that hard land gold-seekers go.\nGold now, in ever dwindling vol\nume, is the chief export. Incredibly\nrich as the soil is, agriculture' is\nlimited by lack of labor. Most of\nthe 'Condamnees,' though farmed\ncut by the government to work for\nprivate masters, are too weak in\nmind or body or both to till the\nsoil in this trying climate. Efforts\nto colonize free men, on a big scale,\nhave brought no good results. The\naverage potential immigrant shuns\nFrench Guiana, because so many\nconvicts are here. But one is amaz\ned at the good order. By seven\no'clock the small town of Cayenne\nis dark.\n\"Dilapidated Cayenne, with weed\njrrown plazas, weather-beaten\nhouses, and its rough streets\ncleaned only by buzzards, is a blot\nof gloom depressings its normal\nsouls. Weeping women and despond\nent men sit idly about its chejp\ncafes or wander under the small\ngrove of strange conspicuous royal,\npalms which lift their graceful\ntrunks above the squalor of its prin\ncipal plaza. 'Liberes,' such half-free\nprisoners are called. Though then\ndays of actual confinement are end\ned, they are at liberty only within\nthe borders of Cayenne. A convict,\nsent here for a term longer than 8\nyears, must remain for life; he is\nknown as a \"prisoner in perpetuity.\nBut a man sent for a lesser period,\nsay for .five years, must remain an\nadditional five in the colony or\none year on the 'island' for each\nyear spent in its jails before he\ncan return to France. Then he mu&t\npay his own way home. For the\nGovernment does not repatriate the\nexiles. Often such a man's relatives\nor friends send him money to come\nhome on; occasionally, he can earn\nenough in the colony. French Arabs,\nindustrious and thrifty, support a\neort of community chest which buys\nhome-bound tickets for each Arab,\nas his day of complete liberty ar\nrives. Gentlemen and Hoodlums Brothers\nin Misery\n\"Lawyers, doctors, engineers, art\nists, skilled artisans as well as\ncriminals from the, peasant class\nand the slums of Paris these you\nsee in the streets. Many seek to\nearn a few francs, at iny kind oi\nwork, in a lost city wnere even\npetty tasks are few.;?-: 'That tall,\nragged, bare-footed man driving\nthat milk-goat from house to house\nis a French gentleman of a fine old\nfamily,\" said my guide.' 'My chauf\nfeur is a convict,' said the Governor\nas we took a short ride around the\ndispiriting place. 'Practically every\nbody you see in the streets is a\nconvict. .The 'liberes' are ree to\nwork for wages, and some of them\nare in partnership with natives In\nvarious kinds of business.' Figur\nines of Jaguars, women and birds,\nbeautifully carved from hardwood\nand even cleverly fashioned little\nTaylor Douthit's home run in the fourth inning of the third game of the World Series was\nenough to down the A's but the Cards went ah ead to score four more, while Hallahan held the\nAmerican leaguers scoreless. Here the Re d Bird outfielder is scoring the home run.\nguillotines, are the work of one\nwho thus gains money for f cham\npagne. He was a successful Paris\nsculptor. The dry Guillotine' is the\nconvicts' grim nickname for this\npenal colony -officially designated\nas such by Napoleon III in 1854.\n\"I killed a centipede in the room\nwhere I slept the night I passed in\nthe penal colony and was glad\nwhen we took the air and flow over\nvapor-draped jung-les in the eany\nmorning down towards the great\nRiver -Oyapock, beyond which lies\nBrazil.\"\nFILES $1200 CLAIM\nIN COLLISION SUIT\nPlainville Motorist Blames Local\nDriver lor Crash\nDamage to his automobile in a\ncollision with a Car owned by Sophie\nChudzik and driven by Zona Chudzik\nof this city is claimed in a $1,200\nsuit Edward J. Lawrence of Plain\nville brought today. The Chudzik\nautomobile has been garnisheed and\nproperty at 325 Broad street was\nattached today by Constable Fred\nWinkle.\nThe accident .occurred on June 21\nlast. The plaintiff claims he was\ndriving at a moderate rate of speed\nin a westerly direction on New\nBritain avenue in Plainville when\nthe defendant's car came in the op\nposite direction, at a high rate of\nspeed and struck tho plaintiff's au\ntomobile. It is alleged the New\nBritain car swung over the left side\nof the highway before the accident\noccurred.\nAttorney Harold N. William of\nNew Britain represents the plaintiff.\nCcnti-Rapelyc Suit Settled\nA suit over an accident at the\ncorner of Allen and Oak streets on\nMay 19 last in which four members\nof one family was involved has been\nsettled. The action was brought\nagainst Mrs. Katherine Rapelye by\nAngelo Centi of 211 Chestnut street,\ndriver and owner of the other car,\nMr. and Mrs. Joseph Biicionis,\nAgnes, Nelda and Alphonse Bucion\nis, all of New Britain, who were\npassengers in Centi's machine.\nThe agreement was reached at a\nconference between Attorney Charles\nW. Tamulonis and officers of the\nAmerican Mutual Liability Insurance\nCo. of Boston.\nThe accident occurred when the\nwheels of the two automobiles be\ncame locked and the plaintiff's car\nwas thrown on its side. The pas\nsengers had to be taken from the\nwindows of the car.\nCity Items\nRev. William A. Harty branch, A.\nO. H., will meet in Judd's hall to\nnight at 7:30 o'clock. A whist card\nparty will folow the reguar meeting.\nHave you played the Indoor Lit\ntle Meadow Golf Course at 147\nMain St, next to Strand Theater?\nDaily prizes. advt.\nA meeting of St. Elizabeth's\ntheatrical circle will be held tonight\nat 8 o'clock at the clubrooms in the\nrectory on Orange street.\nRIDGEFIELD MAN HELD\nNorwalk, Oct. 7 VP) William E.\nHolmes of Ridgeficld was arrested\nhere today on a charge of drunken\ndriving, following an accident in\nwhich Walter Domowski of 348\nStillman aventfe, Bridgeport, was\nslightly Injured. Holmes, driving an\nautomobile owned by Francis Har\ngraves of Norwalk, crashed into the\nrear of a car operated by William\nStodolik of Stamford, in which Do\nmowski was a passenger. Holmes\nwill be tried in city court Saturday.\nTty\nBeef-Loaf\nfSpicy!Different!\nSpread before 1 I\nCooking with LJ\nGULDENS\nrv Mustard\nLEAVESTURKEY\nExpedition Completes Successlul\nSummer of Study\nIstanbul, Turkey, Oct. 7 (P) The\nfifth Anatolian expedition of the\nOriental Institute of the University\nof Chicago left for home today after\na successful archaeological summer,\ndespite the burning heat of Anatolia\nand the menace of malaria.\nThe expedition, led by Dr. Hans\nHenning Van Der Osten and Rich\nard Martin of Chicago, reached the\ndeepest level of Asia Minor's buried\nhistory yet disclosed by archaeolo\ngists. The greatest achievement was the\ndiscovery of a Neolithic level at\nAleshar, about 80 feet below the top\nof an ancient citadel wall, where\nwas bared a fragment of a wooden\nroof dating at least to 10,000 B. C.\nThe Chicagoans thus proved the\nexistence of stone age man in Asia\nMinor where, through digging in\nthe same mound at Aleshar, they\nalready had bared 10 distinct set\ntlements, including the first and\nsecond Hittite empire periods.\nAs the expedition left for Amer\nica it carried the Turkish govern\nment's first archaeological loan to\nany foreigners, including a human\nskeleton 3,500 years old and valuable\ntablets which American scientists\nwill study in seeking to solve the\nHittite mystery. 1\nThe Turkish government gave\nevery assistance to the expedition,\nlargely because of the interest of\nMustapha Kernel, the ghazi, in Hit\ntite research.\nCLINTON HOLSE BURNS\nClinton, Oct. 7 UP) Fire early yes\nterday swept the Clinton House, an\ncient hostelry which has been a\nlandmark here since revolutionary\ndays, causing damage estimated at\n$4,000.\nA young couple stopping at the\nhotel discovered the fire and awak\nened other occupants. All escaped\nsafely. Part of the hotel 'ounge,\nfour rooms and the attic were badly\ndamaged.\nFILES LARGE SUIT\nAGAINSTTRUCKERS\nBridgeport Man Ms $25$0\nDamages lor His Injuries\nInjuries received by Julius Yv'an\nkovits of Bridgeport in an automo\nbile crash on August 22, 1930 are\ntho basis of a $25,000 suit Wanko\nvits brought today against the Con\nsolidated Motor Lines, Inc., of this\ncity.\nThe plaintiff claims he was oper\nating his automobile in a northerly\ndirection at the intersection of Bish\nop and Barnum avenues, Bridgeport,\nwhen the defendant's employe, pro\nceeding in a westerly direction on\nBishop street, struck the plaintiff's\ncar and besides doing damage to\nthe automobile injured the driver.\nIn addition to receiving injuries to\nthe head, body, arms and legs, the\nplaintiff claims internal injuries and\nexpense of hospital treatment.\nAttorney Charles S. Brody of\nBridgeport represents the plaintiff\nand Deputy Sheriff Martin H. Hor\nwitz served the papers.\nRACKETEER FOUND DEAD\nNew York, Oct. 7 (P) Herbert.\nIrving Roberts, notorious gunman\nand racketeer who escaped in 1928\nfrom the Virginia state prison, was\nfound dead early today on the seat\nof an abandoned automobile in a\nresidential section of the Bronx. Po\nlice said he had been taken for a\n\"ride.\"\nKRt'PP MAY CUT FORCE\nEssen, Germany, Oct. 7 (IP) The\nKrupp firm announced today that\nowing to the unfavorable business\noutlook it will be necessary to dis\nmiss 2,500 employes in November\nunless prospects materially improve.\nAVALSH GRANTED DIVORCE\nBridgeport, Oct. 7 W David R.\nWalsh of Poughkeepsie, N. Y today\nwas granted a divorce from Alma\nBreeden Walsh, Stamford physician.\nThe decree was allowed by Judge\nFrederick M. Peasley on a cross\ncomplaint charging desertion. They\nwere married in 1922.\nI SE HERALD CLASSIFIED ADS\nNassau Finance Corporation\n300 MAIN STREET\n5TH FLOOR\nNEW BRITAIN\nLOANS UP TO $300\nYour employer is not notified and there\nis no assignment against your wages.\nOur only charge is SJ4 per cent per\nmonth on the unpaid amount of loan.\nOPEN MONDAY EVENINGS UNTIL 9 O'CLOCK\nWEALTH\nAND\nWELL-TH\n''Health is wealth.\" And what a wealth of\nnewly minted smiles and rosy cheeks,\nstrength and physical fitness come in every\nbottle of Seibert's Milk\nFOUR GLASSES A DAY ASSURES\nVIGOR UNDER ANY RIGOR.\nM0Rfilt1G.h00ri?ainiGHT -w MAKE SURE its seiberts\nJ.E.SEIBERT&SON\n433-435 PARK ST. PHONE:1720\nat RAPHAEL'S\nBUY HERE AND SAVE!\nGOOD QUALITY\nPERCALES\nAll new patterns and de\nsigns. Every yard perfect\nfull pieces.\n\"ESMOND\"\nBUNNY\nBLANKETS\nSize 30x40\nNeatly boxed bunny\nblankets with nursery\npatterns, in pink and\nblue. Value 75c.\nMEN'S\nUNION SUITS\nFall and Winter Weights\n$1.00 Grades\nSPECIAL WEDNESDAY\nr XJJ Jl kJ\nSLIP-ON\nSWEATERS\nSizes 28 to 36\nAttractive new sweat\ners in plain colors or\nneat jacquard patterns.\nStrongly woven for\n